[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026825&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026825&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We do the same re-writing but we do it primarily for a different reason.
For the most reliable mail delivery, we avoid as much strain on IP and
its routers as possible.  The connectivity between the world and a host
directly on the Arpanet is more reliable than to a host on an attached
network, and frequently results not from local routing problems but
remote ones that we have no direct control over.  I know this sometimes
applies to ucb-ether, too.

So we've just been being pragmatic here.  Users like pragmatic mail systems.
That argues for continuing to hide the domain-only names, but it might
be time to use irate users of a host table-only site to encourage those
sites to convert.

As an aside, when something goes wrong it's been useful to have all the
external mail queued up on a single host.  1, you notice trouble
immediately, instead of its being buried on some random workstation, and
2, it's all in one place if there is some ugly kludge one can do to
"fix" it.  Of course, we don't have so much mail as you, and our relay
is an 8600.

